   "photo-caption" : "<p><a class=\"tumblr_blog\" href=\"http://ucresearch.tumblr.com/post/149131772429\">ucresearch</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<h2>Why sunflowers move with the sun</h2>\n<p>You might think that sunflowers gets its name from their similar appearance to the sun, but how they got their name actually has to do with the fact that they are always turned toward the sun.</p>\n<figure data-orig-width=\"480\" data-orig-height=\"270\" class=\"tmblr-full\"><img src=\"https://66.media.tumblr.com/dc5a1a59e5d83e703a2cdf39343c05a7/tumblr_inline_obo4enXBUf1rz05k1_500.gif\" alt=\"image\" data-orig-width=\"480\" data-orig-height=\"270\"/></figure><p>And UC Davis and UC Berkeley researchers have recently discovered the reason behind their quirk.Â <br/></p>\n<p>Under a controlled environment where the light remained constant for 24 hours, the researchers at <a href=\"http://universityofcalifornia.edu/news/why-sunflowers-move-clockwork?utm_source=tumblr&amp;utm_medium=social-organic&amp;utm_campaign=article-general&amp;utm_content=\">UC Davis and UC Berkeley</a> found that the sunflowers still maintained their rhythmic movement.</p>\n<p>When the researchers exposed the plants to a longer light cycle, they found that it disoriented their swaying pattern as if they were experiencing a jet-lag.</p>\n<p>So like animals that have an internal 24-hour clock that responds to light and regulates when to sleep and eat (and other physiological process,) researchers believe that that sunflowers also have this biological circadian rhythm that helps regulate theirÂ growth, which causes those swaying movements. Â </p>\n<p>During the day, one side of the sunflower stem elongates, causing its head to tilt east, and at night time, the other side of the stem stretches, causing its head to tilt west.</p>\n<figure data-orig-width=\"480\" data-orig-height=\"270\" class=\"tmblr-full\"><img src=\"https://66.media.tumblr.com/2e9e7e7a48f8710f4fe41af55c088465/tumblr_inline_obo4ecEdLN1rz05k1_500.gif\" alt=\"image\" data-orig-width=\"480\" data-orig-height=\"270\"/></figure><p>As with any organism behavior, their movement is likely an adaptive trait.<br/></p>\n<p>Researchers found that the flower that faced west (aka the wrong direction) when the sun rose, saw a decrease in growth and attracted fewer pollinators.Â </p>\n<p><i>GIF Source: <a href=\"http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2016/08/why-young-sunflowers-follow-sun?utm_source=general_public&amp;utm_medium=youtube&amp;utm_campaign=vid-sunflower-sun-6304\">Science MagazineÂ </a></i></p>\n</blockquote>",
